		<header>
			
			<h1>Pacific ministers move EPA process forward, but focus on red-line contentious issues</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 September 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In the second week in August 2011, Pacific Island Forum Trade Ministers at their meeting in Port Moresby discussed the drawing up of ‘national plans to gradually reduce duties on imports from the European Union’, in preparation for the next round of EPA negotiations. Addressing Ministers, Pacific Island Forum Secretary General Tuiloma Neroni Slade noted the EC’s insistence on Pacific states tabling ‘revised market access offers’ before the next round of negotiations. He reported that eight PACP governments had already finalised their offers, while four governments still had to develop their market access offers. The Secretary General said that this development ‘now empowers the PACP region to demand of the European Commission reciprocal focus and seriousness about the negotiations and show flexibility.’ Key contentious issues identified included: ‘the issue of development cooperation provisions, export taxes, infant industry, standstill clause, the Most-Favoured Nation provisions, the non-execution clause, taxation and governance issues, market access and rules of origin for fisheries products’.</p><p>The Chair of the Ministerial meeting, Tonga’s Lisiat ’Akolo, described fisheries issues as ‘one of the key contentious issues for the Pacific region in its negotiations with the EU’. Indeed, according to Secretary General Slade, ‘a number of Pacific ACP States have indicated that their market access offers to the European Union in the context of a comprehensive EPA is contingent upon securing global sourcing rules of origin for fresh and frozen fish.’</p><p>Pacific ministers called for increased assistance in support of the Pacific Aid for Trade Strategy established in 2009. Ministerial chair ’Akolo said that Pacific island nations needed ‘aid for trade’ support ‘to address the structural, institutional and capacity challenges that stop Pacific businesses from trading more successfully with other Pacific island countries and with the world.’</p><p>In 2010, some €35 million in ‘aid for trade’ assistance was directed to a range of projects, including ‘improved customs management, support for value chain development and tourism services, and the development of national trade policies’. However this was seen as ‘just a start’. Particular importance was attached to improving transportation and communications infrastructure. According to Minister ’Akolo, ‘many ports in the region are unable to support even a small increase in the volume of export …. Without more effective ports, we simply cannot increase our trade with the world.’</p><p>Secretary General Slade said that since ‘Pacific island countries expend considerable time and resources to negotiate trade agreements with key partners, including the Economic Partnership Agreement with the European Union and PACER Plus with Australia and New Zealand ... It is vital that these agreements result in tangible trade outcomes.’ He argued that for this to occur, ‘Pacific island countries need assistance to expand their supply capacity and build a strong and capable private sector that can take advantage of new market access opportunities.’ </p><p>Secretary General Slade cited the example of EU restrictions on the sale of products of kava (Piper methysticum, a pepper plant used in the region to make a drink with sedative properties) as ‘an excellent example of our region’s need for greater support on trade issues’.</p><p>The acting head of the EU Delegation in the Pacific, Dr Kay Beese, welcomed the progress being made by PACP governments in preparing market access offers and reiterated the EU’s commitment to concluding a comprehensive EPA with the Pacific region. The next round of negotiations between Pacific ACP States and the EU is scheduled for November 2011 in Brussels.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
