<a href="http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/WO1108/S00208/aid-for-trade-addressing-the-pacifics-unique-challenges.htm" target="_self">http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/WO1108/S00208/aid-for-trade-addressing-th...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Agriculture featured very little in the 4-day discussions in Port Moresby until the Friends of Kava tabled their ‘Kava Initiative’. Kava represents one of the few agricultural products where PACP countries have a potential to develop non-traditional exports to the EU. The trade issues surrounding kava exports in the last decade led to the launching of the Kava Initiative. This can be seen as encapsulating the kind of issues which a trade agreement, such as the proposed comprehensive EPA, should seek to address.</p><p>As a fully originating product, kava enjoyed duty-free and quota-free access to the EU market. Market access has however been blocked on SPS grounds, following claims from the German health authority (BfArM) regarding the liver toxicity of certain kava ingredients. Ten years of intense research has so far produced no clear evidence as to the causative role of kava ingredients in liver injury that is maintained by BfArM. This has led to accusations of the use of SPS concerns as a non-tariff barrier (NTB) to trade. The ban, introduced on food safety grounds, results in an annual loss of PACP export earnings of €4 million. </p><p>On the strength of arguments presented in the Kava Initiative, PACP trade ministers have agreed to incorporate this issue in the text of the comprehensive EPA, but have agreed that dealing with this issue should not unnecessarily delay the completion of the comprehensive EPA itself. Provisions of the Initiative will also affect other chapters in addition to agriculture in the comprehensive EPA, e.g. SPS, and Development Cooperation. The latter relates to the possibility of accessing resources needed for the execution of the Initiative. This is likely to impinge on ‘aid for trade’ issues. </p><p>The Kava Initiative could potentially be used as an opportunity to address the wider structural issues related to the EPA (e.g. establishing an objective basis for determining the appropriateness of health-related trade restrictions adopted through the application of the precautionary principle). This would add substance to any comprehensive EPA by providing a framework for addressing non-tariff barriers to market access in areas where PACP states have an export potential.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
